[src:shadow-dom/element-slot] The **`slot`** property of the `Element` interface returns the name of the shadow DOM slot the element is inserted in.
[src:shadow-dom/element-slot] A slot is a placeholder inside a web component that users can fill with their own markup (see Using templates and slots for more information).
[src:shadow-dom/element-slot] In our simple-template example (see it live), we create a trivial custom element example called `<my-paragraph>` in which a shadow root is attached and then populated using the contents of a template that contains a slot named `my-text`.
[src:shadow-dom/element-slot] When `<my-paragraph>` is used in the document, the slot is populated by a slottable element by including it inside the element with a `slot` attribute with the value `my-text`.
[src:shadow-dom/element-slot] In our JavaScript file we get a reference to the `<span>` shown above, then log a reference to the name of the corresponding `<slot>` element.
[src:shadow-dom/using-shadow-dom] An important aspect of custom elements is encapsulation, because a custom element, by definition, is a piece of reusable functionality: it might be dropped into any web page and be expected to work.
[src:shadow-dom/using-shadow-dom] So it's important that code running in the page should not be able to accidentally break a custom element by modifying its internal implementation.
[src:shadow-dom/using-shadow-dom] Shadow DOM enables you to attach a DOM tree to an element, and have the internals of this tree hidden from JavaScript and CSS running in the page.
[src:shadow-dom/using-shadow-dom] This article covers the basics of using the shadow DOM.
[src:shadow-dom/using-shadow-dom] This article assumes you are already familiar with the concept of the DOM (Document Object Model) — a tree-like structure of connected nodes that represents the different elements and strings of text appearing in a markup document (usually an HTML document in the case of web documents).
[src:shadow-dom/using-shadow-dom] You can affect the nodes in the shadow DOM in exactly the same way as non-shadow nodes — for example appending children or setting attributes, styling individual nodes using element.style.foo, or adding style to the entire shadow DOM tree inside a `<style>` element.
[src:shadow-dom/using-shadow-dom] The difference is that none of the code inside a shadow DOM can affect anything outside it, allowing for handy encapsulation.
[src:shadow-dom/using-shadow-dom] Before shadow DOM was made available to web developers, browsers were already using it to encapsulate the inner structure of an element.
[src:shadow-dom/using-shadow-dom] Think for example of a `<video>` element, with the default browser controls exposed.
[src:shadow-dom/using-shadow-dom] All you see in the DOM is the `<video>` element, but it contains a series of buttons and other controls inside its shadow DOM.
[src:shadow-dom/using-shadow-dom] The shadow DOM spec enables you to manipulate the shadow DOM of your own custom elements.
[src:shadow-dom/using-shadow-dom] The shadow tree and `<slot>` elements inherit the `dir` and `lang` attributes from their shadow host.
[src:shadow-dom/using-shadow-dom] We're going to use the `"host"` element as the shadow host.
[src:shadow-dom/using-shadow-dom] We call `attachShadow()` on the host to create the shadow DOM, and can then add nodes to the shadow DOM just like we would to the main DOM.
[src:shadow-dom/using-shadow-dom] Creating a shadow DOM via JavaScript API might be a good option for client-side rendered applications.
[src:shadow-dom/using-shadow-dom] For other applications, a server-side rendered UI might have better performance and, therefore, a better user experience.
[src:shadow-dom/using-shadow-dom] In such cases, you can use the `<template>` element to declaratively define the shadow DOM.
[src:shadow-dom/using-shadow-dom] The key to this behavior is the enumerated `shadowrootmode` attribute, which can be set to either `open` or `closed`, the same values as the `mode` option of `attachShadow()` method.
[src:shadow-dom/using-shadow-dom] After the browser parses the HTML, it replaces `<template>` element with its content wrapped in a shadow root that's attached to the parent element, the `<div id="host">` in our example.
[src:shadow-dom/using-shadow-dom] Note that in addition to the `shadowrootmode`, you can use `<template>` attributes such as `shadowrootclonable` and `shadowrootdelegatesfocus` to specify other properties of the generated shadow root.
[src:shadow-dom/using-shadow-dom] But let's see what happens if code running in the page tries to access elements in the shadow DOM.
[src:shadow-dom/using-shadow-dom] This page is just like the last one, except we've added two `<button>` elements.
[src:shadow-dom/using-shadow-dom] Clicking the "Uppercase span elements" button finds all `<span>` elements in the page and changes their text to uppercase.
[src:shadow-dom/using-shadow-dom] Clicking the "Reload" button just reloads the page, so you can try again.
[src:shadow-dom/using-shadow-dom] In the example above, we pass an argument `{ mode: "open" }` to `attachShadow()`.
[src:shadow-dom/using-shadow-dom] With `mode` set to `"open"`, the JavaScript in the page is able to access the internals of your shadow DOM through the `shadowRoot` property of the shadow host.
[src:shadow-dom/using-shadow-dom] The `{mode: "open"}` argument gives the page a way to break the encapsulation of your shadow DOM.
[src:shadow-dom/using-shadow-dom] If you don't want to give the page this ability, pass `{mode: "closed"}` instead, and then `shadowRoot` returns `null`.
[src:shadow-dom/using-shadow-dom] However, you should not consider this a strong security mechanism, because there are ways it can be evaded, for example by browser extensions running in the page.
[src:shadow-dom/using-shadow-dom] It's more of an indication that the page should not access the internals of your shadow DOM tree.
[src:shadow-dom/using-shadow-dom] In both cases, the styles defined in the shadow DOM tree are scoped to that tree, so just as page styles don't affect elements in the shadow DOM, shadow DOM styles don't affect elements in the rest of the page.
[src:shadow-dom/using-shadow-dom] Rules defined in the `CSSStyleSheet` will be scoped to the shadow DOM tree, as well as any other DOM trees to which we have assigned it.
[src:shadow-dom/using-shadow-dom] An alternative to constructing `CSSStyleSheet` objects is to include a `<style>` element inside the `<template>` element used to define a web component.
[src:shadow-dom/using-shadow-dom] Which of these options to use is dependent on your application and personal preference.
[src:shadow-dom/using-shadow-dom] Creating a `CSSStyleSheet` and assigning it to the shadow root using `adoptedStyleSheets` allows you to create a single stylesheet and share it among many DOM trees.
[src:shadow-dom/using-shadow-dom] For example, a component library could create a single stylesheet and then share it among all the custom elements belonging to that library.
[src:shadow-dom/using-shadow-dom] The browser will parse that stylesheet once.
[src:shadow-dom/using-shadow-dom] Also, you can make dynamic changes to the stylesheet and have them propagate to all components that use the sheet.
[src:shadow-dom/using-shadow-dom] The approach of attaching a `<style>` element is great if you want to be declarative, have few styles, and don't need to share styles across different components.
[src:shadow-dom/using-shadow-dom] Without the encapsulation provided by shadow DOM, custom elements would be impossibly fragile.
[src:shadow-dom/using-shadow-dom] It would be too easy for a page to accidentally break a custom element's behavior or layout by running some page JavaScript or CSS.
[src:shadow-dom/using-shadow-dom] As a custom element developer, you'd never know whether the selectors applicable inside your custom element conflicted with those that applied in a page that chose to use your custom element.
[src:shadow-dom/using-shadow-dom] Custom elements are implemented as a class which extends either the base `HTMLElement` or a built-in HTML element such as `HTMLParagraphElement`.
[src:shadow-dom/using-shadow-dom] Typically, the custom element itself is a shadow host, and the element creates multiple elements under that root, to provide the internal implementation of the element.
[src:shadow-dom/using-shadow-dom] The example below creates a `<filled-circle>` custom element that just renders a circle filled with a solid color.
[src:shadow-dom/using-shadow-dom] For more examples, illustrating different aspects of custom element implementation, see our guide to custom elements.
[src:shadow-dom/using-templates-and-slots] This article explains how you can use the `<template>` and `<slot>` elements to create a flexible template that can then be used to populate the shadow DOM of a web component.
[src:shadow-dom/using-templates-and-slots] When you have to reuse the same markup structures repeatedly on a web page, it makes sense to use some kind of a template rather than repeating the same structure over and over again.
[src:shadow-dom/using-templates-and-slots] This was possible before, but it is made a lot easier by the HTML `<template>` element.
[src:shadow-dom/using-templates-and-slots] This element and its contents are not rendered in the DOM, but it can still be referenced using JavaScript.
[src:shadow-dom/using-templates-and-slots] Although trivial, you can already start to see how this could be useful.
[src:shadow-dom/using-templates-and-slots] Templates are useful on their own, but they work even better with web components.
[src:shadow-dom/using-templates-and-slots] Let's define a web component that uses our template as the content of its shadow DOM.
[src:shadow-dom/using-templates-and-slots] The key point to note here is that we append a clone of the template content to the shadow root, created using the `Document.importNode()` method.
[src:shadow-dom/using-templates-and-slots] And because we are appending its contents to a shadow DOM, we can include some styling information inside the template in a `<style>` element, which is then encapsulated inside the custom element.
[src:shadow-dom/using-templates-and-slots] This wouldn't work if we just appended it to the standard DOM.
[src:shadow-dom/using-templates-and-slots] So far so good, but the element isn't very flexible.
[src:shadow-dom/using-templates-and-slots] We can only display one bit of text inside it, meaning that at the moment it is even less useful than a regular paragraph!
[src:shadow-dom/using-templates-and-slots] We can make it possible to display different text in each element instance in a nice declarative way using the `<slot>` element.
[src:shadow-dom/using-templates-and-slots] Slots are identified by their `name` attribute, and allow you to define placeholders in your template that can be filled with any markup fragment you want when the element is used in the markup.
[src:shadow-dom/using-templates-and-slots] If the slot's content isn't defined when the element is included in the markup, or if the browser doesn't support slots, `<my-paragraph>` just contains the fallback content "My default text".
[src:shadow-dom/using-templates-and-slots] To define the slot's content, we include an HTML structure inside the `<my-paragraph>` element with a `slot` attribute whose value is equal to the name of the slot we want it to fill.
[src:shadow-dom/using-templates-and-slots] If you want to play with it some more, you can find it on GitHub (see it running live also).
[src:shadow-dom/using-templates-and-slots] The `name` attribute should be unique per shadow root: if you have two slots with the same name, all of the elements with a matching `slot` attribute will be assigned to the first slot with that name.
[src:shadow-dom/using-templates-and-slots] But the `slot` attribute does not need to be unique: a `<slot>` can be filled by multiple elements that all have a matching `slot` attribute.
[src:shadow-dom/using-templates-and-slots] The `name` and `slot` attributes both default to the empty string, so elements with no `slot` attributes are assigned to the `<slot>` with no `name` attribute (the unnamed slot, or default slot).
[src:shadow-dom/using-templates-and-slots] The previous example uses *named slot assignment*, which means the named `<slot>` elements in a template are populated with the content of elements in the custom component (or more generally the host element) that have matching names in their `slot` attributes.
[src:shadow-dom/using-templates-and-slots] This is the original mechanism used for slot assignment and is the most suitable method for most use cases.
[src:shadow-dom/using-templates-and-slots] Manual assignment is useful when you want to dynamically select the content to be slotted, or if you want to assign slots based on some other element attribute such as their `id`, without having to add duplicate `slot` attributes.
[src:shadow-dom/using-templates-and-slots] For example, a `<movie-picker>` custom element might use a `<select>` element to filter on genre, slotting only the elements that have a matching `data-genre` attribute value on change.
[src:shadow-dom/using-templates-and-slots] Named slot assignment is the default behavior.
[src:shadow-dom/using-templates-and-slots] On user agents that support setting the shadow root slot assignment method, you can enable this feature when you attach the shadow root.
[src:shadow-dom/using-templates-and-slots] This is done programmatically using the `options.slotAssignment` parameter passed to `Element.attachShadow()`, or declaratively by setting the `shadowrootslotassignment` attribute on the `<template>` element.
[src:shadow-dom/using-templates-and-slots] The following HTML shows a basic example of how you can set `shadowrootslotassignment` when declaratively creating a shadow root (using `shadowrootmode`).
[src:shadow-dom/using-templates-and-slots] To finish off the article, let's look at something a little less trivial.
[src:shadow-dom/using-templates-and-slots] However, it is generally more practical to add slots within a `<template>` element, since you are unlikely to need to define a pattern based on an already-rendered element.
[src:shadow-dom/using-templates-and-slots] In addition, even if it is not already rendered, the purpose of the container as a template should be more semantically clear when using the `<template>`.
[src:shadow-dom/using-templates-and-slots] In addition, `<template>` can have items directly added to it, like `<td>`, which would disappear when added to a `<div>`.
[src:shadow-dom/using-templates-and-slots] Next, let's create a new custom element named **`<element-details>`** and use `Element.attachShadow` to attach to it, as its shadow root, that document fragment we created with our `<template>` element above.
[src:shadow-dom/using-templates-and-slots] This uses exactly the same pattern as we saw in our earlier trivial example.
[src:shadow-dom/using-templates-and-slots] Finally let's put all the snippets together and see what the rendered result looks like.
[src:shadow-dom/web-components] There are two parts to Custom Elements: autonomous custom elements and customized built-in elements.
[src:shadow-dom/web-components] Autonomous custom elements are HTML elements that are entirely separated from native HTML elements; they are essentially built from the bottom up using the Custom Elements API.
[src:shadow-dom/web-components] Customized built-in elements are elements that are built upon native HTML elements to reuse their functionality.
[src:shadow-dom/web-components] The Shadow DOM is a functionality that allows the web browser to render DOM elements without putting them into the main document DOM tree.
[src:shadow-dom/web-components] This creates a barrier between what the developer and the browser can reach; the developer cannot access the Shadow DOM in the same way they would with nested elements, while the browser can render and modify that code the same way it would with nested elements.
[src:shadow-dom/web-components] The impact of CSS scoped within the Shadow DOM of a particular element is that HTML elements can be encapsulated without the risk of CSS styles leaking and affecting elements that they were not supposed to affect.
[src:shadow-dom/web-components] Although these elements are encapsulated with regard to HTML and CSS, they can still fire events that can be picked up by other elements in the document.
[src:shadow-dom/web-components] The scoped subtree in an element is called a shadow tree.
[src:shadow-dom/web-components] The element the shadow tree is attached to is called a shadow host.
[src:shadow-dom/web-components] A Shadow DOM must always be connected to an existing element, either through attaching it as a literal element or through scripting.
[src:shadow-dom/web-components] In JavaScript, Shadow DOMs are attached to an element using `Element.attachShadow()`.
[src:shadow-dom/web-components] An HTML template defines a block of HTML content that is not rendered when the page loads, but can be instantiated during runtime.
[src:shadow-dom/web-components] Scripts within a template do not run, and resources are not fetched, until the content is cloned or added to the DOM.
[src:shadow-dom/web-components] Web Components are supported by current versions of all major browsers.
[src:shadow-dom/web-components] Backward compatibility with older browsers is implemented using JavaScript-based polyfills.
[src:shadow-dom/web-components] There are many libraries that are built on Web Components with the aim of increasing the level of abstraction when creating custom elements.
[src:shadow-dom/web-components] There are numerous community efforts for the Web Components ecosystem.
[src:shadow-dom/web-components] WebComponents.org provides an interface to search for any existing Web Components.
[src:shadow-dom/web-components] Custom Elements Everywhere validates whether popular front-end frameworks are compatible and ready to use Web Components standard, with a set of pending bugs and available workarounds.
[src:shadow-dom/web-components] Moreover, Vaadin Tutorials has a dedicated section that shows how those workarounds are used efficiently with example demo apps and similarly related topics.
[src:shadow-dom/web-components] In 2011, Web Components were introduced for the first time by Alex Russell at Fronteers Conference.
[src:shadow-dom/web-components] In 2013, Polymer, a library based on Web Components was released by Google.
[src:shadow-dom/web-components] Polymer is canonical implementation of Material Design for web application user interfaces.
[src:shadow-dom/web-components] In 2016, RequireJS was introduced as JavaScript library and AMD loader plugin for custom elements.
[src:shadow-dom/web-components] In 2017, Ionic (mobile app framework) team built StencilJS, a JavaScript compiler that generates Web Components.
[src:shadow-dom/web-components] In 2018, Angular 6 introduced Angular Elements that lets you package your Angular components as custom web elements, which are part of the web components set of web platform APIs.
[src:shadow-dom/web-components] In 2018, Firefox 63 enabled Web Components support by default and updated the developer tools to support them.
[src:shadow-dom/web-components] In 2018, LitElement was developed by the Google Chrome team as part of larger Polymer project.
[src:shadow-dom/web-components] LitElement was designed to be a lightweight and easy-to-use framework for creating web components.
